				new listedValue("Pancake Ice (30 cm to 3 m) - Floe Size (FF)", "Predominantly circular plates of ice from 30 cm to 3 m in diameter, and up to about 10 cm in thickness, with raised rims due to the pieces striking against one another. It may be formed on a slight swell from grease ice, shuga or slush or as a result of the breaking of ice rind, nilas or, under heavy swell, of grey ice.",1),
				new listedValue("Shuga/Small Ice Cake; Brash Ice (2 m) - Floe Size (FF)", "An accumulation of spongy white ice lumps, a few centimetres across; they are formed from grease ice or slush and sometimes from anchor ice rising to the surface. Accumulations of floating ice made up of fragments not more than 2 m across, the wreckage of other forms of ice.",2),
				new listedValue("Ice Cake (20 m) - Floe Size (FF)", "Any relatively flat piece of sea ice less than 20 m across.",3),
				new listedValue("Small Floe (20 to 100 m) - Floe Size (FF)", "Any contiguous piece of sea ice, from 20 to 100 metres across.",4),
				new listedValue("Medium Floe (100 to 500 m) - Floe Size (FF)", "A relatively flat piece of sea ice 100 m to 500 m across. Floes are subdivided according to horizontal extent.",5),
				new listedValue("Big Floe (500 to 2000 m) - Floe Size (FF)", "Separate patch of floating ice or flat sheet of unbroken pack ice, greater than 20 metres (22 yards) across. A big floe is a floe of size 500 to 2000 metres across.",6),
				new listedValue("Vast Floe (2 - 10 km) - Floe Size (FF)", "Any contiguous piece of sea ice, 2-10 kilometres across.",7),
				new listedValue("Giant Floe (10 km) - Floe Size (FF)", "A relatively flat piece of sea ice 10 km or more across.",8),
				new listedValue("No Stage of Development - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "No stage of development - ice stage of development (SS).",80),
				new listedValue("New Ice (5 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Recently formed ice which includes frazil ice, grease ice, slush and shuga and which is of less than 5 centimetres thickness. These types of ice are composed of ice crystals which are only weakly frozen together (if at all) and have a definite form only while they are afloat.",81),
				new listedValue("Nilas Ice (10 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "A thin elastic crust of ice, easily bending on waves and swell and under pressure, thrusting in a pattern of interlocking 'fingers' (finger rafting). Has a matt surface and is up to 10 cm in thickness. May be subdivided into dark nilas and light nilas.",82),
				new listedValue("Young Ice (10 to 30 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Ice in the transition stage between nilas and first-year ice, 10-30 cm in thickness. May be subdivided into grey ice and grey-white ice.",83),
				new listedValue("Grey Ice (10 to 15 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Young ice 10-15 cm thick. Less elastic than nilas and breaks in swell. Usually rafts under pressure.",84),
				new listedValue("Grey - White Ice (15 to 30 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Young ice 15-30 cm thick. Under pressure it is more likely to ridge than to raft.",85),
				new listedValue("First Year Ice (30 to 200 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "The ages and thicknesses of the ice. First year ice is sea ice of not more than one winter's growth, developing from young ice; thickness 30 cm - 2 m, and sometimes slightly more.",86),
				new listedValue("Thin First Year Ice (30 to 70 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "First-year ice 30-70 cm thick.",87),
				new listedValue("Thin First Year Ice Stage 1 (30 to 50 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "First-year ice 30-50 cm thick.",88),
				new listedValue("Thin First Year Ice Stage 2 (50 to 70 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "First-year ice 50-70 cm thick.",89),
				new listedValue("Medium First Year Ice (70 to 120 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Sea ice of not more than one winter's growth, developing from young ice; thickness 70 cm - 120 cm.",91),
				new listedValue("Thick First Year Ice (120 cm) - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "First-year ice over 120 cm thick.",93),
				new listedValue("Residual Ice - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "First-year ice that has survived the summers melt and is now in the new cycle of growth. It is 30 to 180 cm thick depending on the region where it was in summer. After 1 January (in the Southern hemisphere after 1 July), this ice is called second-year ice.",94),
				new listedValue("Old Ice - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Sea ice which has survived at least one summer's melt; typical thickness up to 3m or more. It is subdivided into residual first-year ice, second-year ice and multi-year ice.",95),
				new listedValue("Second Year Ice - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Old ice which has survived only one summer's melt; typical thickness up to 2.5 m and sometimes more. Because it is thicker than first-year ice, it stands higher out of the water. In contrast to multi-year ice, summer melting produces a regular pattern of numerous small puddles. Bare patches and puddles usually greenish-blue.",96),
				new listedValue("Multi-Year Ice - Ice Stage of Development (SS)", "Old ice up to 3 m or more thick that has survived at least two summers' melt. Hummocks are even smoother than in second-year ice and attain a look of mounds and hills. The surface of multiyear ice fields in places not subject to deformations is also hillocky due to non-uniform multiple melting. The ice is almost salt-free. Its color, where bare, is usually blue. As a result of melting, round puddles appear at its surface in summer and a well-developed drainage system is formed.",97),
				new listedValue("Undetermined/Unknown", "Having an unknown value.",99),
			];

